Glove Transmitter — How the code works
Setup:
On boot the ESP32 initializes Serial at 115200 baud, sets GPIO 13 and 14 as input pullup pins for the conductive probe triggers, and initializes the MPU6050 over I²C. ESP-NOW is initialized in station mode and both drone MAC addresses are registered as peers. The glove's own MAC address is printed to Serial so you can verify it matches what's in the receiver code.
Main Loop (runs at 50Hz):

Trigger detection — GPIO 13 and 14 are read. LOW means the wire is touching ground — that drone is selected and active.
IMU reading — Raw accelerometer and gyroscope data is read from MPU6050 in one call.
Angle calculation — If any trigger is active, pitch and roll angles are computed using atan2 from accelerometer axes. These give the tilt angle of your hand in degrees.
Smoothing — An exponential filter (α = 0.15) smooths the raw angles to remove noise. Lower α = smoother but more lag.
Deadzone — Any angle within ±5° is treated as zero. This filters natural hand tremor so the drone doesn't drift when your hand is still.
RC mapping — Filtered angles (-45° to +45°) are mapped linearly to RC values (1350 to 1650 microseconds), centered at 1500 (neutral).
Packet build — A ControlPacket struct is filled with fly_active = true, the pitch and roll RC values, and fixed values for throttle and yaw (handled by receiver).
Transmission — The packet is unicast via ESP-NOW to whichever drone's trigger is active. The inactive drone always receives a stop packet with fly_active = false.

Tuning constants at the top:

TILT_SENSITIVITY — how much the drone responds to tilt
SMOOTHING — noise filtering vs responsiveness
TILT_DEADZONE — tremor filtering threshold

